This is pretty simple using [`Files.find()`][1] to walk a directory tree looking for matching files, and [`Collectors.groupingBy()`][2] to convert that stream into the desired map.

```java
import java.io.IOException;
import java.nio.file.Files;
import java.nio.file.Path;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Map;
import java.util.stream.Collectors;

public class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        for (String dir : args) {
            try (var files = Files.find(Path.of(dir), 256,
                                        (p, attr) -&gt; p.getFileName().toString().endsWith(&quot;.po&quot;))) {
                Map&lt;String, List&lt;Path&gt;&gt; po_files =
                    files.collect(Collectors.groupingBy(p -&gt; p.getParent().toString()));
                System.out.println(po_files);
            } catch (IOException e) {
                System.err.println(e);
                System.exit(1);
            }
        }
    }
}
```

This will give you a map where the keys are paths to directories, and the values are lists of paths to all the `.po` files in those directories.


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/nio/file/Files.html#find(java.nio.file.Path,int,java.util.function.BiPredicate,java.nio.file.FileVisitOption...)
  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/util/stream/Collectors.html#groupingBy(java.util.function.Function)

